The old dog trotted down the quiet street with the kind of confidence that only comes from years of knowing exactly where every interesting smell lives. 
His ears flicked at the distant hum of traffic, but his tail swayed in an easy rhythm, unbothered by the world rushing around him. When he reached the corner, 
he paused, lifted his head, and let the breeze wash over his face. It carried the scent of morning bread from the bakery, a hint of rain on warm pavement, 
and—most importantly—the familiar footsteps of the person he loved most. With a soft huff of recognition, he broke into a gentle, joyful run, 
as if every day were a reunion worth celebrating.